@Gavin Gibson 
Hey Gavin, 
I sincerely could not agree more with you, and I'm sure Mr. Rhodes agrees too. I also noticed that most people tend to spend less money on their rings. There is not a spike at $15k, but rather the $15k group is an aggregate value of all values greater than $15,000, and that is why there is an increased quantity at that value.

comment info:
Question:  Can we assume the end ranges of income level keep the same average percent spent on engagement rings?  

People who make from $10,000 to $23,000 spend ($1,670 to $3,841 per ring on average)
from $23,000 to $40,000 spend ($920 to $1,600 on avg)
from $40,000 to $58,000 spend ($1,480 to $2,146 on avg)
from $58,000 to $90,000 spend ($1,798 to $2,790 on avg)
from $90,000 to $163,300 spend ($2,790 to $5,062 on avg)
from $163,300 to $207,351 spend ($5,062 to $6,427 on avg)
from $207,351 to $518,400 spend ($6,427 to $16,070 on avg)
from $518,400 to $1,000,000 spend ($16,070 to $31,000 on avg)

It makes me wonder:
Why the lowest income level has the higher end limit in their range of money spent on the ring ($3,841)?

Is the median income range of those polled lower than $23,000 annually?

Do more people in a lower income bracket decide to propose on Valentine's day (compared to those in a higher income bracket)?  If so, can those help make a case that marketing efforts, advertising companies, are doing a good job of targeting this lower income bracket?

Clever title:
Cupid targets the low-income bracket
